She flipped to an empty page and noted the date. Below that, she wrote "11.5.648–13.12.648".
"Are you reviving old memories?" Ivory asked and looked at the old notebook. Kari nodded. "Do you think they'll let you out for Christmas? It's just a few days away."
Kari knocked twice on the lantern. "No," as Ivory had suspected. The Ice King never allowed Kari to leave because he considered her a "blemish." She was born deaf and was the only daughter in the family; her brothers were all boys.
The same was true for Ivory. When Ivory came out as non-binary, it seemed like the world was changing around her. As punishment for this difference, Ivory received tasks where she was mostly alone.
Additionally, Ivory was also forced to serve the princess. But it didn't bother her much since she gained a friend in the process.
“You have a birthday coming up, right?” asked Ivory, as she remembered that the princess would have her birthday in a few days. Kari nodded with a sad sparkle in her light blue eyes.
“Do you want to celebrate your birthday?” asked Ivory, thinking back to the last time the princess had answered this question.
“No,” said Kari. Ivory knew this was a difficult topic for her. Her birthday was the day she was locked in this room and her mother was banished. At that time, Ivory was just a baby, but she remembered how upset the servants and the city’s residents were. Ivory had heard that Eirwen was a popular queen and strangely could even predict things that would later come true.
“Well, what do you want to do?” asked Ivory. Kari looked excitedly at Ivory. She held a piece of paper in her hand. On it was written:
15 x 15 cm canvas
White, various shades of blue
Pencils in six different sizes
Easel
“These things should I get for you?” Ivory asked the quiet princess whose pigtails swayed back and forth due to her vigorous knocking. “Yes?” Ivory giggled softly. The usually closed-off princess showed such enthusiasm. It was the first time she had asked for something that had nothing to do with books and came from outside her room.
“Okay! See you later?” Ivory asked, stood up, and wove her way through the chaos of papers and notebooks.
Kari nodded, turned back to her notes, and wrapped herself in her blanket.
Ivory left the room, relieved that the princess had finally stepped out of her comfort zone and asked for things beyond her usual reach, like Malfarben.
Ivory walked through the corridors again, trying to ignore the gossip of the maids.
“I heard she is obsessed with Queen Eirwen and therefore keeps going into this room.”
“I heard she eats children in this room.”
“She looks like a man, that’s not normal, right?”
Ivory covered her ears because she simply couldn’t ignore the chatter and continued walking. The room of the royal painter was located in the east wing behind the second door on the left.
Ivory approached the door, which was just as intricately decorated as Kari’s door. On it was the White Dragon, one of the six Urdragons allegedly created by Frostfall. For a history-loving painter, the White Dragon on the door made perfect sense.
Ivory opened the door and expected the usual chaos. Splashes of paint everywhere, brushes and papers scattered throughout the room, canvases covering every inch of the wall. To her surprise, however, a different scene greeted her. The entire room was clean, and in front of a background of red velvet stood a stool. On the stool sat Crown Prince Aquilo, who was being painted.
“Good morning, Ivory! Would you like to watch your future king being painted?” asked Aquilo and winked at Ivory.
“Excuse me, little prince,” said Ivory, largely ignoring him and gathering together the things that the quiet princess desired. “I’m only here to get painting supplies.”
“My little girl wants to go already?” asked Aquilo. “But I want you to stay!”
“I do not.” Ivory found the painting supplies on the list and put them in a box. “Moreover, I am not a girl.”
The prince, however, had a different opinion. “Oh sweetie, that’s just a phase! As you grow older, you’ll outgrow it!” he said indistinctly.
“I have to go,” said Ivory, feeling uncomfortable by the prince’s response. She remembered all the ugly comments he and others had made about her gender identity in the past. I just want to leave here.
“Are you leaving already?” Suddenly, the prince appeared at the door and ignored the loud objections of the royal painter.
“This is not behavior for a future king!” said Ivory.
“No one will find out. People won’t believe you and the painter will keep quiet if his life means anything to him.” He looked at the painter briefly and then leaned closer to Ivory. “What do you think about a date?” Ivory had been harassed multiple times before, but never by a prince and certainly not by the crown prince.
“Do you actually know what the word ‘no’ means?” Ivory spat out and pushed the crown prince away.
“No,” answered Aquilo with a smile. Of course, the crown prince, who can have whatever he wants, doesn’t know what the word “no” means.
Ivory rolled her eyes. "Why would you want to date someone like me? You must have around 100 admirers,"
he interrupted Ivory, still smiling. He threw back his hair, which swirled in the cold air.
"Get it through your head! Why me? I'm a threat to the palace." Ivory crossed her arms.
"You are the most beautiful girl I have ever seen." Aquilo lifted Ivory's chin with his finger and forced her to look at him.
